node.text: Discovering my new favourite book shop with @rosie_saunt - which publishes out of print writing by female authors. @persephonebooks sell their books - elephant grey book jacket and printed inside with a pattern that specifically relates to the year they were originally published, with every print created by a female artist - at bookshops like Daunt, but their office/shop on Lambs Conduit Street is def the best place to appreciate their collective magic. My favourite title there is ‚ÄúHow To Manage A House Without Staff‚Äù (1953 - can‚Äôt remember the author) which is all the more hilarious for how radical a concept that would have been to a middle class household in the 50s, and also, ‚ÄúThe Home Maker‚Äù (1924) about a house husband (an even more radical concept at the time of publication.) It seems only fitting that the woman who introduced me to this hive of work by courageous woman, is the bravest woman I know. üíõ

I‚Äôm a huge fan of all these artists (I bloody love a female nude, including those by other Partnerships artist, @juliannabyrne) and I am endlessly impressed by @georgiaspray who founded Partnership Editions a mere 2 years and has already changed the landscape of affordable art, into something genuinely creative, free from pretension and full of joyful and interesting dialogue that I want to be a part of. I have a new column for @elleuk üòÅ Online, bi-monthly, social commentary and not unlike the fodder we cover on The High Low. For my inaugural column, I tackle The OOO. I am - like many people - ob-sessed with Alan Partridge‚Äôs OOO which went viral at the BBC. But nestled in the satire is a truth: is the automated-response function a handy tool; or a desperate attempt to resist our incessant culture of communication? Amidst drowning in my inbox and detonating OOOs like they were flare guns, I wrote this. Link in bio. (And yes, that man who simply writes ‚Äònope‚Äô on his OOO is my hero.)

Today‚Äôs episode of The High Low is one of the most important - and certainly prescient - author specials we have ever had. Journalist and author, Fatima Bhutto (the niece of assassinated Pakistani Prime Minister, Benazir Bhutto) came on to talk about her new novel, The Runaways, an account of 3 teenagers who join ISIS. Fatima discusses what might make a teenager like Shamima Begum join a terrorist group (‚Äúthey‚Äôre searching for a type of freedom. It might not look like freedom to you and me - but they are looking for somewhere to belong‚Äù) and what the West does not understand about radicalism. She also said something that I cannot stop thinking about - I‚Äôve relayed it below. For further reading, there‚Äôs an excellent interview with Fatima in The Sunday Times Magazine yesterday, by Decca Aitkenhead (link in Stories.) It‚Äôs a flammable topic - and not everyone will agree with Fatima - if you‚Äôd like to join in the conversation, please e-mail thehighlowshow@gmail.com rather than doing so via DM, or in the comment section.

‚ÄúWhen I hear things like ‚Äòwestern values‚Äô I never understand what that means. Does that mean, if you come from the East, you don‚Äôt value freedom? Is tolerance not an eastern value, too? That has always been disturbing to me. The idea that there are these two spots in the world at constant friction with each other ‚Äî I don‚Äôt think that exists. My experience is that people in Pakistan want the same thing as people in Britain. They want a safe life. A sense of belonging. They want to be able to live lives that they can be proud of. I don‚Äôt think that‚Äôs a Western idea. I think that‚Äôs a human one.‚Äù

If you thought you‚Äôd heard me wang on enough already about how good Portobello market is for vintage shopping: YOU AIN‚ÄôT. I‚Äôm trying to make sure I wear a bit of vintage every day (I don‚Äôt always succeed, but that‚Äôs my base endeavour) and over London Fashion Week that included my favourite vintage Gucci wool blazer, which you‚Äôve probably seen me wear a gazillion times and my white cardigan, both from Portobello. Sustainability isn‚Äôt just an ethical concern; it‚Äôs a fiscal one. Put simply, we need to find ways of culturally placing less fiscal and more emotional value on clothes. Vintage shopping is fiscally sustainable as much as it is emotional - case in point: the Gucci blazer was ¬£50 and the cardi was ¬£30. About the same price as the lower end of the high street. I am so pleased to share a longform essay I‚Äôve been working on for the last few months, called The Authentic Lie. 
It will be published through the independent crowd-funding publisher @_pound_project - a brilliant venture which supports writers and gives them the freedom to write their dream piece, with (!!!) no word count - and features a foreword by the magnificent award-winning author @elizabday. 
It‚Äôs about the modern obsession with authenticity - finding it, anchoring it, framing it - in a hyper-curated world. It deals with womanhood, self-image, celebrity, social media and the concept of ‚Äòlikeability‚Äô in order to ask, what makes an authentic life?
It also draws on the words of lots of brilliant writers (thank you, so much, to everyone who contributed). You can pledge to read it online or in mini book format, in the link in my bio! It will be released in March.

‚ÄúThe real pain isn‚Äôt in the leg being mangled. It‚Äôs in the way the bone sets.‚Äù This is the most difficult book I‚Äôve ever read. I sobbed everywhere, while reading Jayson Greene‚Äôs Once More We Saw Stars (don‚Äôt let the Disney title put you off): in bed; on the tube; in the hairdresser. But it was precisely *because* it was so hard to read, that I thought it so important to do so. The phrase ‚Äòreading for pleasure‚Äô carries the subtext that what we read, should be pleasurable; easy. But I choose to read things that jar me and occasionally, even, cause me physical pain. I am particularly interested in grief, at the moment - I, personally and we, Western society as a whole, fear it so entirely - and reading this book felt a little like reading a long-form version of Rob Delaney‚Äôs astounding, recent interview with Decca Aitkenhead in The Sunday Times, on the engulfing grief of losing a young son. I am always reluctant to play ‚Äòthe parent card‚Äô (‚Äúthis affected me more because I have a child‚Äù) but I found it almost impossible not to conflate my baby daughter with young Greta Greene - not least because their hair tufts over their ears in exactly the same way. The book comes out in May 2019 (I suggest you pre-order it now) and it has taught me so much about grief. That it isn‚Äôt always silent and humble. It is also angry and vain-glorious. Grief is so many things, because people are so many things. I wish with all my heart that Greta Greene was still with her parents. But in her absence, I can only thank her father for his memoir about what loving her, and losing her, taught him.

When I was pregnant, I was astounded by how many people asked ‚Äòif‚Äô I‚Äôd go back to work - the subtext, which stubbornly prevails, being that the man is the primary earner - and how many of those, some friends, who suggested that I wouldn‚Äôt need childcare. That because I am freelance, I could produce what has become an exhaustive volume of work, including the production of an entire weekly podcast, ‚Äòaround‚Äô the baby. I also realised, when I hired my nanny (8am-6pm, 4 days a week, which are the hours I work) that there is still so much guilt around women and childcare. Having a nanny is a mark of privilege. A lot of women work their ass off and cannot afford one; I am lucky that working my ass off means that I can. It was also essential for me, in order to return to work 5 weeks post-partum, that my daughter was looked after at home. I don‚Äôt have any shame about my nanny, anymore. Her name is Mimi. She‚Äôs one of the best women in my life. She helped me put myself back together. She makes my baby happy. She makes ME happy. And she sure as fuck isn‚Äôt paid for by my ‚Äòhobbies‚Äô.

The last squish I met at the Princess Anne Hospital in Southampton with @pampersuk_ire was Baby Xander. Xander, my friends, has no time for dilly-dallying. Forget 24 hours spent pacing over a box set; his mother‚Äôs entire active birth took less time than an episode of Eastenders. Maureen had a natural birth, without any gas and air, or even paracetamol - but it was not planned that way. ‚ÄúI am terrified of pain‚Äù laughs Maureen. ‚ÄúI wanted an epidural, like I‚Äôd had with my first baby. But there wasn‚Äôt any time.‚Äù Xander was born 8 days early during a consultation in an assessment room - before they could get her to the labour ward - after just one push. If her 2 babies have taught her anything (her older son Riley is 21 months) it is that you cannot plan anything. ‚ÄúPrepare for the unknown! I didn‚Äôt get my epidural, but it all worked out for the best.‚Äù Thank you, Pampers, for this wonderful experience. Lots of other stories by me, on their feed now! #pampers #deliveredwithlove

Introducing you to baby Adam, just one day old (spot the teeny face), who I met on my trip with @pampersuk_ire to Princess Anne Hospital in Southampton. His mum, Riya, had such severe hyperemesis gravidarum (chronic morning sickness) while pregnant that she was hospitalised for 3 weeks. Riya knew she would be seriously unwell throughout her pregnancy - she had suffered from hyperemesis while pregnant with her first son, Kevin, aged 6. She was terrified about attempting a second pregnancy. ‚ÄúWe had to really think about it‚Äù says her husband, Jobin, who was dashing between work, the hospital and his son while Riya was sick. ‚ÄúCould we deal with this, again?‚Äù Many women are sick, or intensely nauseous during their pregnancy, but Riya was sick every single minute that she was awake. Even a drop of water would make her vomit. She lost a lot of weight and begun vomiting blood. ‚ÄúThe doctors said they had never seen anything like it‚Äù says Riya. 
Happily, Riya had a swift, natural labour and her sickness disappeared as soon as Adam appeared. ‚ÄúI had Kevin in India, so this is also my first experience of the NHS. The mental health support here is amazing. I felt like I could get through anything. But no more babies!‚Äù @pampersuk_ire #pampers #deliveredwithlove

One of the first babies I met on my recce of the Princess Anne Hospital in Southampton (whose brilliant maternity unit is one of the units covered for One Born Every Minute, FYI) was Valerie. Valerie Blythe is a bit of a miracle baby. Starved of oxygen for 12 minutes during birth, after complications with her mother Kayla‚Äôs epidural and subsequent spinal block, cerebral palsy was a real fear.
Valerie received 72 hours of ‚Äòcooling therapy‚Äô from neonatal nurses in NICU, a relatively new treatment in babies who are deprived of oxygen at birth to prevent brain damage by reducing body and brain temperature. Kayla didn‚Äôt get to hold her baby, until she was 5 days old. Her father held her on the 6th. 
Kayla is visibly emotional when discussing her traumatic birth - but it is when talking about her gratitude for the midwives, that she (and I - I‚Äôve got to be honest) are overwhelmed with tears. As it‚Äôs half-term, and I‚Äôm forever welded to the scholastic year, I thought I‚Äôd share a pr√©cis of the books I‚Äôve read since the summer. I‚Äôm addicted to reading - I‚Äôm in 4/5 nights a week (like most people with a 7 month old baby) and switch off my phone/ the telly after 8pm - and I sometimes wonder if I devour the literature of others as a tool to distract myself from doing the thing I love and fear most: writing. Instagram therapy session over... a line on the books. I‚Äôve read some wonderful fiction of late. I devoured Seven Days of Us (the debut novel by @theststyle alumni Francesca Hornak) in 24 hours - keenly observed and utterly believable, it reminded me of One Day and is destined to be a hit. Late In The Day is another stinger from Tessa Hadley - proof again that the ‚Äòdomestic novel‚Äô (to borrow Meg Wolitzer‚Äôs words) can be as sharp as any political thriller. Putney by Sofka Zinovieff - dubbed ‚ÄúLolita for the #MeToo generation‚Äù by one critic - is a discomfiting read about the lies we tell ourselves. While I didn‚Äôt hugely enjoy Angela Chadwick‚Äôs xx - a nutopian‚Äô read about a clinical trial which allows 2 women to have a (female only) biological baby - it‚Äôs a provocative, timely premise. The 2nd novel from Graham Norton, The Keeper is an original and moving tale of family secrets, which deftly weaves between 2 generations in Ireland and my mum is going to LOVE it. And some stellar non-fiction: Tuesdays with Morrie, recc by a High Low listener, is a sweet little book written over 20 yrs ago, about a dying professor imparting philosophical lessons to his beloved, now grown-up student. Dopesick by Beth Macy is a deep-dive into America‚Äôs heroin epidemic, which begun with the mass prescription of OxyContin in the 90s, whilst Matt Haig‚Äôs Notes on A Nervous Planet is the most accurate book I‚Äôve ever read about anxiety: the way worry coats itself in further worries. Lastly, In Extremis by Lindsey Hilsum - a funny, frank and moving biography about The Sunday Times war correspondent Marie Colvin, who died in Syria in 2012. Lindsey came on to this wk‚Äôs The High Low to talk about her friend Marie and what it is like to report from the most dangerous places in the world.

I‚Äôm a born sharer of the personal, but recently I‚Äôve been hesitant to share in the same way. The internet scares me; and I feel sick most of the time I put anything on Instagram. I love people who share everything about their parenting - it‚Äôs inclusive and generous and helpful - but I‚Äôm not comfortable inviting commentary into that part of my life. A lot of the time, The High Low just feels like an excuse for @dollyalderton and I to grill women we admire. Today‚Äôs episode (#64 but whose counting) is one of those days. Elizabeth Uvibinen√© and Yomi Adegoke wrote Slay In Your Lane: The Black Girl Bible because there was not one single book - nope, not one - that either of them could find, about British black women. That addressed micro-aggressions and invalidations; that diversity (and the beauty industry) so often only extends to bi-racial women and not, as Yomi says, ‚Äúthe darkest dark‚Äù; that there are myriad shocking stats (only 0.49% of university professors are black women; black women are 3 times more likely to get breast cancer; black women are swiped left on Tinder more than any other ethnic group) that we *should* be talking about in our wider culture conversation and yet, somehow, aren‚Äôt. Yomi and Elizabeth couldn‚Äôt find the book they desperately needed; and so they wrote it themselves. For young British black women, they hope they this book will function as both a validation and a working tool. For everyone else, this book isn‚Äôt *for* you - but you should read it anyway, because it‚Äôs lively and thoughtful and jam-packed with statistics and interviews with successful women. I look forward to it changing if not the world, then certainly our conversations within it. Link in bio!

Today‚Äôs episode of The High Low is a bit of a special (and meta) one: with the CREATOR of high/low journalism, iconic editor Tina Brown. My piece with @ulrikkehoyer in today's Times newspaper. Ulrikke (the current face of Chloe) and casting director @jamespscully both had so many revealing things to say - so I've included a bit more, below. üîπ As James told me yesterday - "eating disorders were not rife on the catwalks in the 80s. Linda; Christy; Cindy -- none of those women were encouraged not to eat. We wonder why influencers are doing so well -- it's because people can't relate to the girls they see on the catwalk. The Kardashians offer them a body that fashion just isn't providing." üîπFor every dunce who believes eating disorders are a 'given' in the modelling industry, it's worth remembering that these girls don't enter the industry with one. "They start modeling aged 15, before puberty hits" James told me. "It used to be 18." It's when their body starts to inevitably change that they become encouraged to fit restrictive measurements. "The dress used to fit the girl" says James. "Now the girl fits the dress." Ulrikke says, "a girl who is too small for a size zero dress sample? Not a problem, make the dress smaller. A girl who is too big for a size zero sample? BIG problem." üîπWhat's more depressing now is that modelling has become 'two tier', explain both Ulrikke and James. "It's so unfair' says Ulrikke "that there are different rules for different models." The Instagram girls, the Victoria's Secret Angels with their millions of followers, are allowed to inhabit whatever body type they want. Why? Because they have power. They have money. (And, incidentally, that success is due to the fact that they have an athletic body more in-line with the 80s model who was slim, sure, but not bony. It's what the consumer wants to actually SEE.) 'Catwalk cattle' like Ulrikke - successful, but globally anonymous - have a different set of rules imposed on them.
üîπThe worst bit about all this? "We're talking about 0.5cm" Ulrikke told me tiredly. Yes: 0.5cm. 
Thank you to them both for giving me their first interviews. I can't wait to hear more from both of them.
